(420, 1, '2015-02-20 16:58:06', '2015-02-20 16:58:06', 'Bridgeland is unveiling its newest community - Hidden Creek - and launching new homesites in its Traditional Neighborhood Design development (TND), Lakeland Heights, with a grand opening event that offers participants a chance at winning $2,500. From February 23<sup>rd</sup> until March 8th, the general public is invited to tour model homes located in the community. Upon completion of visiting all 11 homes, participants will be given a scratch-off ticket valued anywhere from $10 to $100. One lucky winner, selected at random, will walk away with the grand prize of $2,500. Additionally, homebuyers that sign a contract during the grand opening will receive a $1,000 gift card after closing.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n<div class="media media-element-container media-default"><img class="media-element file-default alignright" src="http://www.bridgeland.com/sites/default/files/Tree%20House%20Park.jpg" alt="" width="517" height="291" />\r\n<div class="field field-name-field-modal-link field-type-link-field field-label-hidden field-wrapper"> Hidden Creek is the largest section to open to date in Bridgeland with 1,000 homesites set alongside 142 acres of lakes and waterways. New luxury homes range in price from $300,000 to over $1 million and are built by Beazer Homes, Darling Homes, Meritage Homes, Perry Homes, Ryland Homes, Taylor Morrison Homes, Village Builders and Westin Homes.</div>\r\n</div>\r\n“We’re excited to show off Hidden Creek,” said Peter Houghton, Vice President of Master Planned Communities for Bridgeland. “The opening of our largest neighborhood comes at an exciting time given the tremendous demand for upscale homes in the northwest Houston area. Bridgeland continues to attract buyers with its wide range of desirable housing, resort-style amenities and top-notch schools.”\r\n\r\nIn addition to being the newest and largest community within Bridgeland, Hidden Creek will introduce an extensive array of amenities, including Lakeland Village Park, a 20-acre green space that will feature an enclosed dog park, basketball court, canoe launch and skate park. Additional tennis courts, picnic areas, walking trails and pavilions are also planned as well as a new splash pad, playground and heated lap pool, which will be open year-round.\r\n\r\nOne of the most anticipated amenities in Hidden Creek, Tree House Park, will feature a whimsical, two-story tree house nestled among live oaks that date back to the property’s early rice farming days. Adjacent to the custom-built piece, a boardwalk will hover over an old creek bed and a decomposed granite pathway will wind through the wooded area nearby. The remainder of the park will be left in its natural state, one of Bridgeland’s many efforts to preserve and restore its land, which is located on the Katy Prairie.\r\n\r\nSimilar to other sections of Lakeland Village, an extensive trail system will be nestled within Hidden Creek, including a 12-foot-wide hike-and-bike trail that will follow along Bridgeland Creek Parkway and Josey Ranch Road. The trail will eventually lead directly to Bridgeland’s Town Center, where the community’s dining, shopping, entertainment and employment venues will be located.\r\n\r\nLakeland Heights, the community’s Traditional Neighborhood Design development (TND), is also included in the tour, as the section features a new townhouse product by Perry Homes and new models from David Weekley Homes and J. Kyle Homes.  As a TND development, Lakeland Heights was created to have the aesthetic appeal and accessibility of classic Houston neighborhoods like The Heights and West University, but with the updated amenities of a new community. Consequently, homes are walking distance from parks, recreational facilities and schools. Eventually, residents will also be able to easily access shops and restaurants in Lakeland Village Center, which anchors the 350-home community.\r\n\r\nBridgeland won the 2013 “Master Planned Development of the Year” award from the Greater Houston Builders Association (GHBA), just one of the more than 100 accolades the community has received.', 'Bridgeland Hosts Grand Opening Event for Hidden Creek February 23 - March 8', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'bridgeland-hosts-grand-opening-event-for-hidden-creek-february-23-march-8', '', '', '2015-09-24 17:00:46', '2015-09-24 17:00:46', '', 0, 'http://bridgeland.jmmcdigitalhosting.com/?p=420', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(421, 1, '2015-09-24 16:58:18', '2015-09-24 16:58:18', '15,000 attendees and 10,486 pounds of wild animals filled Oak Meadow Park at Bridgeland on Saturday, May 2<sup>nd</sup> for the eighth Nature Fest, an annual event that brings attention to the award-winning master planned community’s commitment to the environment and ecosystem. The star of the show, Jack Hanna, entertained three jam-packed audiences with a number of exotic companions, including a baby bear, an eagle, a kangaroo and a toucan.  Watch the video <a href="https://youtu.be/9Ipuw6Bnds4">here!</a>\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n<div class="media media-element-container media-default">\r\n\r\n<img class="media-element file-default" src="http://www.bridgeland.com/sites/default/files/Nature%20Fest%20One.jpg" alt="" width="2100" height="1249" />\r\n<div class="field field-name-field-modal-link field-type-link-field field-label-hidden field-wrapper"></div>\r\n</div>\r\nThousands of guests purchased tickets for pony rides, arts-and-crafts and an on-site petting zoo, helping raise more than $3,500 for a local charity that builds housing for families in need throughout Harris County. Since its inception, Nature Fest has enabled Bridgeland to donate nearly $35,000 to local non-profits.\r\n\r\n“We’re thrilled that this year’s Nature Fest was another success,” said Peter Houghton, Vice President of Master Planned Communities for Bridgeland. “Welcoming and offering the general public a day of fun in Bridgeland is something we truly enjoy doing, especially when we’re also able to raise money to put back into the community at the same time.”\r\n\r\nGuests enjoyed concessions from 20 local food trucks, roaming entertainers, educational reptile shows, unique goods from nature vendors and a kids’ zone that featured armadillo races, paddle boat rides, outdoor laser tag, an inflatable zone, a rock wall and a trackless train.\r\n\r\nNature lovers that sponsored the event included <a href="http://www.charlesdyeriv.com/"><u>Charles E. Dyer IV, DDS, MS, PC</u></a>, a returning Title Sponsor,<a href="http://avanti-sl.com/"><u>Avanti Senior Living Towne Lake</u></a>, <a href="http://www.beazer.com/"><u>Beazer Homes</u></a>, <a href="http://www.browngay.com/"><u>Brown &amp; Gay Engineers, Inc.,</u></a> <a href="http://www.costelloinc.com/"><u>Costello</u></a>, <a href="http://davidweekleyhomes.com/"><u>David Weekley Homes</u></a>, <a href="http://www.deltawestenv.com/"><u>Delta West Environmental</u></a>, <a href="https://www.directenergy.com/"><u>Direct Energy</u></a>, <a href="http://www.superdave.com/home.php"><u>Flory Team,</u></a> <a href="http://www.fcer.com/"><u>First Choice Emergency Room</u></a>, <a href="http://www.gulfcoastcorp.com/"><u>Gulf Coast Landscaping Services, Inc</u></a>., <a href="https://www.heb.com/"><u>H-E-B Fairfield</u></a>, <a href="http://landology.net/"><u>LANDology</u></a>, <a href="https://www.libertymutual.com/andreashotwell"><u>Liberty Mutual</u></a>, <a href="http://www.ljaengineering.com/"><u>LJA Engineers, Inc.,</u></a> <a href="http://mcguyerhomebuilders.com/"><u>MHI Homes</u></a>,<a href="http://www.perryhomes.com/"><u>Perry Homes</u></a>, <a href="http://waterworks.pepperconstruction.com/"><u>Pepper Lawson Waterworks</u></a>, <a href="http://www.bridgeland.com/houstonpettalk.com"><u>Pet Talk Magazine</u></a>, <a href="http://www.pcmi-us.com/"><u>Planned Community Management</u></a>, <a href="http://www.rkci.com/"><u>Raba Kistner</u></a>, <a href="http://www.republicservices.com/"><u>Republic Services</u></a>, <a href="http://www.rgmiller.com/"><u>R.G. Miller Engineers, Inc.</u></a>, <a href="http://www.sphllp.com/"><u>Schwartz, Page &amp; Harding L.L.P.</u></a>, <a href="http://www.severntrentservices.com/"><u>Severn Trent Services</u></a>, <a href="http://www.taylormorrison.com/new-homes/texas/houston/cypress/bridgeland-community"><u>Taylor Morrison Homes</u></a>, <a href="http://www.terrainsolutionsinc.com/"><u>Terrain Solutions, Inc</u></a>., <a href="http://www.texaspremierdental.com/"><u>Texas Premier Dental</u></a>, <a href="http://www.realestatewithamy.com/"><u>The Lippincott Team</u></a>, <a href="http://www.thelittlegym.com/houstoncopperfieldtx"><u>The Little Gym of Copperfield</u></a>, <a href="http://www.trueimageortho.com/"><u>True Image Orthodontics</u></a>, <a href="http://www.villagebuilders.com/index.aspx"><u>Village Builders</u></a>, <a href="http://www.westin-homes.com/"><u>Westin Homes</u></a>, Allgreen Associates, Grindel Consulting,  Municipal Accounts and Consulting and UT Physicians.\r\n\r\nNature Fest was titled “2014 Event of the Year” by the Greater Houston Builders Association. Bridgeland also hosts another large community event in October called Howl-O-Ween Fest.', 'Bridgeland''s Nature Fest Featuring Jack Hanna Attracts 15,000 People', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '408-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-09-24 16:58:18', '2015-09-24 16:58:18', '', 408, 'http://bridgeland.jmmcdigitalhosting.com/408-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(422, 1, '2015-09-24 16:58:40', '2015-09-24 16:58:40', 'We hope you’re getting excited about Nature Fest this Saturday! The Bridgeland Development Team has worked diligently over the last seven months to plan an event that the entire family can enjoy. Here are some day-of logistics:\r\n<p align="center"><strong>8<sup>th</sup> Annual Nature Fest</strong></p>\r\n<p align="center"><strong>Saturday, May 2<sup>nd</sup></strong></p>\r\n<p align="center"><strong>Oak Meadow Park</strong></p>\r\n<p align="center"><strong>10 a.m. – 5 p.m.</strong></p>\r\n<p align="center"><!--more--></p>\r\n<strong><em>Parking:</em></strong> There will be a total of 12 shuttle stops this year - 11 in the neighborhood and one in the green space that’s between Warner Elementary School and Smith Middle School. The link to the map that follows (also below) only shows stops within Bridgeland, please follow directional signage on Fry to get to the 12th stop between Warner and Smith.<span class="file"><img class="file-icon" title="application/pdf" src="http://www.bridgeland.com/modules/file/icons/application-pdf.png" alt="" /><a href="http://www.bridgeland.com/sites/default/files/Shuttle%20Map.pdf" type="application/pdf; length=3626556">Download Download Download Download Download Shuttle Map.pdf</a></span>\r\n<div class="media media-element-container media-default">\r\n\r\n<img class="media-element file-default" src="http://www.bridgeland.com/sites/default/files/Shuttle%20Map.jpg" alt="" width="1539" height="1189" />\r\n<div class="field field-name-field-modal-link field-type-link-field field-label-hidden field-wrapper"></div>\r\n</div>\r\nFor the first time since we’ve hosted Nature Fest, we will not be utilizing Cy-Ranch’s parking lot because of school-related activities taking place on Saturday. Consequently, we’ve reserved space at Warner Elementary, Smith Middle School and in the open field in front of Lake Bridgeland.\r\n\r\nWith that being said, we kindly request that residents consider the following options before parking at any of the previously-mentioned locations:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Walk to your nearest shuttle stop and have a bus take you to Oak Meadow Park</li>\r\n	<li>Walk or bike to Oak Meadow Park – bike racks will be available at Oak Meadow Park</li>\r\n	<li>If space is available, park at Pope Elementary and take a shuttle to Oak Meadow Park</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nFor those who need it, handicap parking is located at the front entrance of Oak Meadow Park.\r\n\r\n<strong><em>Attire:</em></strong> Please consider wearing closed-toed shoes or tennis shoes to the event, as stickers can be found throughout Oak Meadow Park’s grass. We also encourage bug spray and sunscreen!\r\n\r\n<strong><em>Activity Tickets:</em></strong> While admission to Nature Fest is free, pony rides, arts-and-crafts activity, face painting and petting zoo <strong>require tickets</strong>. Tickets are $1 each and can be purchased throughout the park on the day of the event*. <strong>The</strong> <strong>petting zoo and pony rides require three tickets each. The arts-and-crafts activity and face painting will require two tickets each</strong>. A portion of the funds raised will benefit Habitat for Humanity Northwest Harris County\r\n\r\n<em>* Cash only. There will be two ATMs on-site at Nature Fest.   </em>\r\n\r\n<strong><em>Other Activities:</em></strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Jack Hanna performances at 12 p.m., 1:30 p.m. and 3 p.m.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Autograph sessions following 12 p.m. and 1:30 p.m. performances</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Sky Kings Falconry shows at 11:30 a.m., 2:30 p.m. and 4 p.m.</li>\r\n	<li>Crocodile Encounter shows at 12:30 p.m. and 3:30 p.m.</li>\r\n	<li>Smith Middle School Band performance at 10:30 a.m.</li>\r\n	<li>Texas Stars Youth Choir performance at 11 a.m.</li>\r\n	<li>Exotic Petting Zoo</li>\r\n	<li>Armadillo Races</li>\r\n	<li>Face Painting</li>\r\n	<li>Kids’ Inflatable Zone</li>\r\n	<li>Rock Wall</li>\r\n	<li>Pony Rides</li>\r\n	<li>Fly Fishing Demonstration</li>\r\n	<li>Trackless Train</li>\r\n	<li>Arts-and-crafts Tent</li>\r\n	<li>Paddle Boat Rides</li>\r\n	<li>Smilebooth Photo Op</li>\r\n	<li>Farmers Market</li>\r\n	<li>Outdoor Laser Tag</li>\r\n	<li>Roaming Street Performers</li>\r\n	<li>Nature Exhibitors</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong><em>Food Trucks</em></strong>: 19 <a href="http://www.bridgeland.com/events/nature-fest">food trucks</a> will be on-site at Nature Fest\r\n\r\n<strong><em>Pictures:</em></strong> We love interacting with event attendees on social media! At the event, be sure to tag <strong>#NatureFest15</strong>and<strong> #BridgelandBalance</strong> in your pictures. We’re looking forward to seeing Nature Fest through your eyes.\r\n\r\n<em><strong>Residents </strong></em><em><strong>Entering/Exiting Bridgeland: </strong></em>Excluding homeowners in First Bend, residents should be able to enter and exit the community through Hidden Pass and can consequently avoid congestion on North Bridgeland Lake Parkway.\r\n\r\nIf you have any questions or concerns, feel free to call the Welcome Center at 281.304.5588. You can also easily reach us via <a href="https://www.facebook.com/Bridgelandcommunity?ref=hl">Facebook</a>.\r\n\r\nHope you all have a wild time on Saturday!', 'Nature Fest Parking and Logistics', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '410-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-09-24 16:58:40', '2015-09-24 16:58:40', '', 410, 'http://bridgeland.jmmcdigitalhosting.com/410-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(423, 1, '2015-09-24 16:59:18', '2015-09-24 16:59:18', 'Bridgeland is showcasing new models and homesites in Lakeland Heights®, a walkable, Traditional Neighborhood Development (TND) where Main Street-style housing blends with shops, parks, restaurants and services, all following guidelines meticulously crafted by architectural powerhouse Looney Ricks Kiss (<a href="http://www.lrk.com/">LRK</a>).\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n<div class="media media-element-container media-default">\r\n\r\n<img class="media-element file-default" src="http://www.bridgeland.com/sites/default/files/Bridgeland%20Lakeland%20Heights_2.jpg" alt="" width="1024" height="670" />\r\n<div class="field field-name-field-modal-link field-type-link-field field-label-hidden field-wrapper"></div>\r\n</div>\r\nDefining elements of Lakeland Heights include its close proximity to Lakeland Village Center, Bridgeland’s first commercial area, rear-access garages and abundant green space. A highlight of the unique community is its half-mile waterway, featuring a landmark bridge, trails, creatively landscaped park space and seating areas.\r\n\r\nStarting in the $250s, homes in Lakeland Heights are built by David Weekley Homes and J. Kyle Homes, while the area’s townhouse product is constructed by Perry Homes.\r\n\r\n“We envisioned Lakeland Heights as a community where you’d see neighbors greet each other from their front porches and meet up at local parks, and we’ve seen that come to fruition since the neighborhood opened in 2010,” said Peter Houghton, Bridgeland’s Vice President of Master Planned Communities. “LRK extensively researched traditional Houston neighborhoods, including The Heights, West University Place, Southampton and Southside Place, for architectural inspiration, enabling us to create something that’s completely new to the Cypress area.”\r\n\r\nPlanned for 350 homes, Lakeland Heights incorporates Craftsman, English Tudor, Classical and French housing styles to heighten curb appeal. Diverse architectural styling that is historical in appearance is a recognizable feature of TNDs.\r\n\r\nHomes’ exterior cladding is made-up of brick, stucco or wood. Set behind the homes, garages are accessed via private rear lanes. Streetlights are reminiscent of those in River Oaks and other historic neighborhoods. Despite the nostalgic architecture, homes will have the modern features today’s buyers expect, such as high ceilings, large closets, media rooms and state-of-the-art kitchens and bathrooms. Additionally, the townhomes in the TND are a part of a new ‘lock-and-leave program’ that includes all yard work and exterior maintenance, allowing for stress-free upkeep.\r\n\r\nMany of the homesites face the waterway or a neighborhood park, and schools, churches and the Lakeland Village Center — a market square with shopping, services and dining — will be within walking distance. Also nearby is the Lakeland Activity Center, with an aquatic complex, tennis courts, boating and a 6,000-square-foot community center.\r\n\r\nGathering spots in Lakeland Heights include Festival Park, with a covered pavilion and Central Park, which includes two acres of green space, an open play area and a formal garden. The three-acre Rabbit Run has active open space and is across the street from the Lakeland Activity Center.\r\n\r\nTo receive information on available homesites in Lakeland Heights, visit <a href="http://www.bridgeland.com/">www.bridgeland.com</a> or call 281.304.5588. You can also view a video of Lakeland Heights <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=09fPfcjmB28">here</a>.', 'New Models and Homesites Available in Lakeland Heights', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '412-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-09-24 16:59:18', '2015-09-24 16:59:18', '', 412, 'http://bridgeland.jmmcdigitalhosting.com/412-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(424, 1, '2015-09-24 16:59:27', '2015-09-24 16:59:27', 'http://www.youtube.com/embed/2hBAPrwYINo\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\nWith striking cinematography and an unforgettable sound track, the newest <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2hBAPrwYINo">television commercial</a> for Bridgeland® highlights the amenity-rich and nature-oriented lifestyle for which the 11,400-acre master planned community has become known. With more than 3,000 acres dedicated to lakes, trails and parks, Bridgeland offers the tranquility of a seemingly untouched natural environment while also providing the convenience of modern facilities – elements the community’s marketing team and advertising agency strived to depict in the newest spot.\r\n\r\nThe commercial debuted in February to coincide with the grand opening of Hidden Creek, the largest section built within Bridgeland thus far with 1,000 homesites set along 142 acres of lakes and waterways.\r\n\r\n“We wanted viewers to really get a strong sense for what life in Bridgeland is truly like,” said Lona Shipp, Bridgeland’s Marketing Manager. “Together with John Manlove Marketing &amp; Communications, we established a vision for the commercial that featured emotional, memorable imagery and a beautiful balance of lyrics and melody.”\r\n\r\nAlongside the vibrant footage shot on-site by Kerry Shaw Brown of LA.B Films, the team worked with Pure Evil Music to develop an original song that would resonate with target audiences. After auditioning multiple singers, the team chose 24-year-old, Dallas-based performer Riley Deaver.\r\n\r\n“Riley''s voice has that undeniable character we were looking for - she''s a little jazzy, a little folksy and her style really worked for the song," said Gary Parks, Pure Evil Music’s Senior Composer.\r\n\r\nImmediately following the commercial’s debut, viewers began to inquire about downloading the song. As a result, <a href="https://itunes.apple.com/album/id968434629" target="_blank">“We’ve Arrived,” featuring Riley Deaver by Hook Society</a> is now available on iTunes and all other major digital music sites.\r\n\r\n“It’s exciting to watch an up-and-coming artist like Riley Deaver take another step towards becoming a household name,” said Shipp. “With the help of Manlove, LA.B Films, Pure Evil Music and Riley’s incredible vocal abilities, we have created a spot that truly captures the essence of Bridgeland.”\r\n\r\nJoining long-time animal advocate and TV personality, Jack Hanna, Riley Deaver will perform ‘We’ve Arrived’ on May 2 at <a href="http://www.bridgeland.com/nature-fest">Nature Fest</a>, an annual event that celebrates Bridgeland’s commitment to the area’s environment and ecosystem.\r\n\r\nTo view the commercial or other community videos, visit <a href="http://www.youtube.com/BridgelandTV">www.youtube.com/BridgelandTV</a>.', 'Newest Bridgeland Commercial Highlights Community Amenities', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '414-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-09-24 16:59:27', '2015-09-24 16:59:27', '', 414, 'http://bridgeland.jmmcdigitalhosting.com/414-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(425, 1, '2015-09-24 17:00:46', '2015-09-24 17:00:46', 'Bridgeland is unveiling its newest community - Hidden Creek - and launching new homesites in its Traditional Neighborhood Design development (TND), Lakeland Heights, with a grand opening event that offers participants a chance at winning $2,500. From February 23<sup>rd</sup> until March 8th, the general public is invited to tour model homes located in the community. Upon completion of visiting all 11 homes, participants will be given a scratch-off ticket valued anywhere from $10 to $100. One lucky winner, selected at random, will walk away with the grand prize of $2,500. Additionally, homebuyers that sign a contract during the grand opening will receive a $1,000 gift card after closing.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n<div class="media media-element-container media-default"><img class="media-element file-default alignright" src="http://www.bridgeland.com/sites/default/files/Tree%20House%20Park.jpg" alt="" width="517" height="291" />\r\n<div class="field field-name-field-modal-link field-type-link-field field-label-hidden field-wrapper"> Hidden Creek is the largest section to open to date in Bridgeland with 1,000 homesites set alongside 142 acres of lakes and waterways. New luxury homes range in price from $300,000 to over $1 million and are built by Beazer Homes, Darling Homes, Meritage Homes, Perry Homes, Ryland Homes, Taylor Morrison Homes, Village Builders and Westin Homes.</div>\r\n</div>\r\n“We’re excited to show off Hidden Creek,” said Peter Houghton, Vice President of Master Planned Communities for Bridgeland. “The opening of our largest neighborhood comes at an exciting time given the tremendous demand for upscale homes in the northwest Houston area. Bridgeland continues to attract buyers with its wide range of desirable housing, resort-style amenities and top-notch schools.”\r\n\r\nIn addition to being the newest and largest community within Bridgeland, Hidden Creek will introduce an extensive array of amenities, including Lakeland Village Park, a 20-acre green space that will feature an enclosed dog park, basketball court, canoe launch and skate park. Additional tennis courts, picnic areas, walking trails and pavilions are also planned as well as a new splash pad, playground and heated lap pool, which will be open year-round.\r\n\r\nOne of the most anticipated amenities in Hidden Creek, Tree House Park, will feature a whimsical, two-story tree house nestled among live oaks that date back to the property’s early rice farming days. Adjacent to the custom-built piece, a boardwalk will hover over an old creek bed and a decomposed granite pathway will wind through the wooded area nearby. The remainder of the park will be left in its natural state, one of Bridgeland’s many efforts to preserve and restore its land, which is located on the Katy Prairie.\r\n\r\nSimilar to other sections of Lakeland Village, an extensive trail system will be nestled within Hidden Creek, including a 12-foot-wide hike-and-bike trail that will follow along Bridgeland Creek Parkway and Josey Ranch Road. The trail will eventually lead directly to Bridgeland’s Town Center, where the community’s dining, shopping, entertainment and employment venues will be located.\r\n\r\nLakeland Heights, the community’s Traditional Neighborhood Design development (TND), is also included in the tour, as the section features a new townhouse product by Perry Homes and new models from David Weekley Homes and J. Kyle Homes.  As a TND development, Lakeland Heights was created to have the aesthetic appeal and accessibility of classic Houston neighborhoods like The Heights and West University, but with the updated amenities of a new community. Consequently, homes are walking distance from parks, recreational facilities and schools. Eventually, residents will also be able to easily access shops and restaurants in Lakeland Village Center, which anchors the 350-home community.\r\n\r\nBridgeland won the 2013 “Master Planned Development of the Year” award from the Greater Houston Builders Association (GHBA), just one of the more than 100 accolades the community has received.', 'Bridgeland Hosts Grand Opening Event for Hidden Creek February 23 - March 8', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '420-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-09-24 17:00:46', '2015-09-24 17:00:46', '', 420, 'http://bridgeland.jmmcdigitalhosting.com/420-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
