(498, 1, '2014-03-28 20:05:59', '2014-03-28 20:05:59', 'Between performing, teaching classes and giving back to the local community, the lives of Chloé St-Jean-Richard and Reyie Delgado are a little like a three-ring circus, something the young, spunky duo is quite familiar with, as they’re the leaders of <a href="http://cirquelavie.wix.com/cirquelavie#!members/c786">Cirque La Vie</a>, a Houston-based circus company.\r\n\r\nAfter a serendipitous meeting at the National Circus School of Montreal in 2006, St-Jean-Richard and Delgado stayed in touch while traveling and training with different groups. However, when Delgado  decided to start his own circus company in 2013, St-Jean-Richard moved from her Canadian hometown to join him in Houston, forming Cirque La Vie. Now, along with a team of five other performers, the  group is beginning to garner attention for its unique choreography and daring acts.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\n“We feel lucky because Houston has really responded to us,” said St-Jean-Richard. “There are no other major circus companies here and people love our acts because they are original.”\r\n\r\nGiven the phrase ‘Dare to be Different’ is stamped on all of the group’s promotional materials, it’s not surprising  St-Jean-Richard was quick to answer when asked what made Cirque La Vie unlike other  groups of its kind.\r\n\r\n“For us, it’s not just about being on stage,” she said. “We want to share what we can do with other people – especially those that don’t have the resources, like time and money, to learn or condition for a  circus performance.”\r\n\r\nThis mindset spurred St-Jean-Richard’s and Delgado’s involvement with a community program called Cirque du Monde, which was started by Cirque De Soleil as a way to instill at-risk youth with self-worth  and confidence by teaching them to master circus techniques. The pair hopes to start a Houston affiliate for the program, or something similar, soon. They also offer $15 community training classes at their  studio and free, hands-on demonstrations after their shows, something they’ll do after their performance on April 26 at <a href="http://www.google.com/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=1&amp;ved=0CCsQFjAA&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.bridgeland.com%2Fnature-fest&amp;ei=5G00U9KkEcewyQHh7oGAAw&amp;usg=AFQjCNGxWkhFDW4InC_QZvYv73IezSBDOA&amp;sig2=LpUWPa4RKXFJffSxZ1q0fA&amp;bvm=bv.63808443,d.aWc">Nature Fest</a>, a family-oriented festival in<a href="http://www.bridgeland.com/home/">Bridgeland</a>.\r\n\r\n“After our routine is over, we will teach the audience how to walk the tight wire, which kids get really excited about,” said St-Jean-Richard. “But even during the show, we are going to interact with the crowd  and really get them involved in the act.”\r\n\r\nCirque La Vie will perform its Circus Safari show at Nature Fest. The eccentric, animal-themed performance, which will combine comedic routines with juggling and stunts, is just one of the many wild aspects of the festival, which will take place from 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. at Oak Meadow Park, 17730 House Hahl Road. To learn more about Nature Fest, visit<a href="http://www.bridgeland.com/nature-fest">www.bridgeland.com/nature-fest</a>.', 'Cirque La Vie Juggles Performing, Teaching and Serving', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'cirque-la-vie-juggles-performing-teaching-and-serving', '', '', '2015-09-24 20:06:32', '2015-09-24 20:06:32', '', 0, 'http://bridgeland.jmmcdigitalhosting.com/?p=498', 0, 'post', '', 0),
