(517, 1, '2014-01-09 20:13:37', '2014-01-09 20:13:37', 'According to an <a href="http://www.chron.com/neighborhood/cyfair/news/article/Cy-Fair-plans-through-2020-5121617.php">article</a> from the Houston Chronicle, officials from the <a href="http://www.chron.com/?controllerName=search&amp;action=search&amp;channel=neighborhood%2Fcyfair%2Fnews&amp;search=1&amp;inlineLink=1&amp;query=%22Cypress-Fairbanks+school%22">Cypress-Fairbanks school</a> district are starting the new year off by creating a comprehensive,multiyear plan to go through 2020, with the possibility of a bond election in May. <span class="caption none media-image alignright size-medium wp-image-2218"><a href="http://www.bridgeland.com/files/cy-fair-article-300x1164jpg"><img class="alignright" src="http://www.bridgeland.com/sites/default/files/styles/medium/public/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Cy-Fair-Article-300x116_4.jpg?itok=kXqH1cjH" alt="Cy-Fair Article" width="220" height="85" /></a></span>\r\n\r\nA newly created planning committee will look at growth, infrastructure, security and technology and assess the need for a bond program, Superintendent <a href="http://www.chron.com/?controllerName=search&amp;action=search&amp;channel=neighborhood%2Fcyfair%2Fnews&amp;search=1&amp;inlineLink=1&amp;query=%22Mark+Henry%22">Mark Henry</a> said.\r\n\r\n"This district continues to grow," he said. "We continue to be a very popular place for people to relocate. We''re probably in there with the top three fastest growing districts in the state."\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\nHenry said the district adds an average of 2,000 students a year.\r\n\r\nThe last bond election was held six years ago, with a projection to last five years, he added.\r\n\r\n"The economy inside the state of Texas and throughout the country went through the great recession and several building projects were delayed," Henry said. "The continued growth of the area needs to be addressed."\r\n\r\nHe said the planning committee will involve the community in evaluating the need and scope for a bond issue.\r\n\r\n"The charge for this process committee is to develop a long-range plan," Henry said.\r\n\r\nThe committee''s recommendation should meet the district''s needs for the next six years.\r\n\r\n"That''s why we have 2020 vision," Henry said.\r\n\r\nAddressing the student growth will be a top concern for the committee, he said.\r\n\r\n"This district has a long history of continuing to look at buildings that have been here the longest and continue to upgrade those facilities so they are equal to our new facilities," Henry said.\r\n\r\nHe said that security enhancements are another major issue - which could include changes in building design and the addition of security cameras.\r\n\r\n"With recent high-profile events that have occurred, we can never be too vigilant in making sure our students and staff are taken care of," Henry added.\r\n\r\nHe explained that technology will be another major component of the plan.\r\n\r\n"As fast as technology is changing, we not only have instructional needs, we also have some infrastructure needs," Henry said.\r\n\r\nHe said even if students bring their own tablets and devices to school, the current system would not have enough capacity to handle it.\r\n\r\n"There are certainly a lot of issues that need to be addressed," Henry said.\r\n\r\nThe committee will also consider increasing bus service to previous levels – requiring additional vehicles, drivers and facilities.\r\n\r\n"We would like to restore transportation to the level of service offered prior to the 2009 -10 school year," Henry said.\r\n\r\nThe committee will be chaired by <a href="http://www.chron.com/?controllerName=search&amp;action=search&amp;channel=neighborhood%2Fcyfair%2Fnews&amp;search=1&amp;inlineLink=1&amp;query=%22Debbie+Blackshear%22">Debbie Blackshear</a>, recently retired from a 28-year career at the <a href="http://www.chron.com/?controllerName=search&amp;action=search&amp;channel=neighborhood%2Fcyfair%2Fnews&amp;search=1&amp;inlineLink=1&amp;query=%22Cy-Fair+Credit+Union%22">Cy-Fair Credit Union</a>.\r\n\r\nBlackshear also serves on the <a href="http://www.chron.com/?controllerName=search&amp;action=search&amp;channel=neighborhood%2Fcyfair%2Fnews&amp;search=1&amp;inlineLink=1&amp;query=%22Cy-Fair+Chamber+of+Commerce%22">Cy-Fair Chamber of Commerce</a>, the <a href="http://www.chron.com/?controllerName=search&amp;action=search&amp;channel=neighborhood%2Fcyfair%2Fnews&amp;search=1&amp;inlineLink=1&amp;query=%22Cy-Fair+Educational+Foundation%22">Cy-Fair Educational Foundation</a>, Cy-Hope board of directors and the president''s advisory committee of the <a href="http://www.chron.com/?controllerName=search&amp;action=search&amp;channel=neighborhood%2Fcyfair%2Fnews&amp;search=1&amp;inlineLink=1&amp;query=%22Lone+Star+College+System%22">Lone Star College System</a>.\r\n\r\nBlackshear has worked on several bond steering committees in the past including 2004 and 2007.\r\n\r\n"Debbie combines intellect, excellent communication skills, unquestionable integrity and a passion for students and public education," Henry said.\r\n\r\n"I feel honored and so fortunate that Debbie is willing to take on this task."\r\n\r\nBlackshear will be joined by Cy-Fair ISD administrative staff members, including associate superintendent of governmental relations and communications <a href="http://www.chron.com/?controllerName=search&amp;action=search&amp;channel=neighborhood%2Fcyfair%2Fnews&amp;search=1&amp;inlineLink=1&amp;query=%22Teresa+Hull%22">Teresa Hull</a>; associate superintendent of facilities, construction and support services <a href="http://www.chron.com/?controllerName=search&amp;action=search&amp;channel=neighborhood%2Fcyfair%2Fnews&amp;search=1&amp;inlineLink=1&amp;query=%22Roy+Sprague%22">Roy Sprague</a>; and associate superintendent of business and financial services, Stuart Snow.\r\n\r\nAbout 50 community members - parents, staff and business associates - will also serve on the committee.\r\n\r\nAfter assessing the district''s needs, the committee is expected to compose recommendations for a bond election date - either in May or November.\r\n\r\n"The date of that election will be important," Henry said.\r\n\r\n"If it''s in May, some of the areas that I''ve addressed could start being solved. If it''s November, this board will have to make some budget priorities for 2014-15."\r\n\r\nHull said the committee will have a head start thanks to preliminary work conducted by Sprague.\r\n\r\n"We started this process several months ago, really trying to look at the needs across the district," she said.\r\n\r\nSprague began evaluating district needs earlier this year.\r\n\r\n"He put a plan together to start assessing all of the facilities," Hull noted.\r\n\r\nThe past fall was spent in discussions about a long-range plan.\r\n\r\nIn October, Sprague distributed facility questionnaires to all principals and administrators. He asked for requests for renovation, maintenance and improved security.\r\n\r\nSprague then scheduled architects to begin conducting walkthroughs of all facilities, Hull said.\r\n\r\nThe walkthroughs will continue through January\r\n\r\n"We''ve started the process of organizing committees - will continue to add members through the month," Hull said.\r\n\r\nShe explained that a May election may seem too soon.\r\n\r\n"But keep in mind, that a lot of work has already been done as far as assessment of facilities and looking and evaluating the needs across the district," she said. "We''ve been working and doing that over the last couple of months."\r\n\r\nHull said that this committee will also be different from other bond committee, because it will not be broken into individual subcommittees.\r\n\r\n"It is our recommendation that we keep the committee together and educate them on all areas so they can make an informed decision in all areas," she said.\r\n\r\nThe first committee meeting was scheduled for Jan. 7 and the rest of the month will be dedicated to discussions of demographics, security and new campuses needed.\r\n\r\nOn Jan. 22, the board of trustees will meet with the committee to evaluate its recommendations.\r\n\r\nHull said that online and telephone services may be used to gather input from the community.\r\n\r\n"Technology and social media actually provide new outlets for us to solicit input and feedback from the community," she said.\r\n\r\nA vote on the long-range plan will be presented to trustees on Jan. 29 and further planning is scheduled in February.\r\n\r\nOn Feb. 27, the board of trustees may hold a specially-called meeting to meet the timeline for a May election.\r\n\r\nIf the committee proposes a bond, Hull said that March would be spent developing information and materials to educate the public about the bond process.\r\n\r\nThe bond election could then been held on May 10 - and work on bond issues could be started over the summer.\r\n\r\n"I think there are some definite benefits of going with the May election," Hull said.', 'Cy-Fair ISD Continues to Expand', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'cy-fair-isd-continues-to-expand', '', '', '2015-09-24 20:14:11', '2015-09-24 20:14:11', '', 0, 'http://bridgeland.jmmcdigitalhosting.com/?p=517', 0, 'post', '', 0),
